    order: '1',
    text: 'There is decent electronic storage, but it is difficult to access - Board members usually need help navigating to the information.',
    detailed: null,
    score: '4.00',
    is_triggering_action: '1',
    risk_id: '20',
    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      'Board related information should be readily and easily accessible at all times.  Boards should establish information architecture and storage protocols, covering:\n\n - What information should be available to Board members;\n - What information is subject to access constraints (who can see\/edit\/update what);\n - The classes of information to be stored, including Board meeting papers, meeting minutes, policies, practices, procedures, HR-related, donor and program related, and so on;\n - What systems which information is stored on, such as straight storage systems (eg Dropbox, Google Drive, Microsoft OneDrive, websites or intranets) or application systems such as Board management systems (eg Convene, OurCatHerder, BoardPro), and\n - A directory stating what is stored where\n\nInformation is often suited to a particular platforms - policies are great on intranets, CEO reviews are not.  While it is ok to have information secured on more than one fit-for-purpose platforms, Boards should avoid spreading information across a multiplicity of platforms as this creates an inherent barrier to access.',
    created_at: '2024-09-10 21:49:50',
