    id: '25',
    question_id: '11',
    order: '1',
    text: 'We have a document that describes our generic roles and responsibilities as Board members.',
    detailed: null,
    score: '6.00',
    is_triggering_action: '1',
    risk_id: '10',
    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "Having individually documented, up to date roles and responsibilities for Board members is not a legal requirement in Australian jurisdictions, but it is considered best practice.  \n\nDocumenting board member roles and responsibilities provides clarity about the specific duties and expectations associated with each position, their individual roles within the broader context of the organisation's governance structure and how their contributions support the achievement of the organisation's mission, vision, and strategic objectives.\n\nDocumented roles and responsibilities also establish a framework for holding board members accountable for their actions and decisions. By clearly delineating expectations, it becomes easier to assess individual performance and address any gaps or shortcomings.\n\nFurther, clearly defined roles and responsibilities facilitates healthy Board dynamics by setting boundaries and expectations for collaboration, communication, and decision-making processes, fostering a more cohesive and productive board environment.\n\nFinally, documenting board member roles and responsibilities facilitates succession planning by providing a roadmap for recruiting, onboarding, and transitioning board members. \n\nThe Board should define roles and responsibilities for each Board member.  Use our Template: Board Roles and Responsibilities as a sound starting point.",
    created_at: '2024-09-10 21:49:50',
