      'Related party transactions involve financial dealings or arrangements between a charity and parties with a close relationship to the charity.  Appropriately identifying and managing related party transactions is required as part of ensuring that responsible persons "act honestly", as required by ACNC Governance Standard 5.\n\nYour Ministry should check and ensure that any policy and processes in place for dealing with related party transactions meet the following criteria:\n\n - Clear definitions of ‘related party’ and ‘related party transactions’;\n - The requirement for all board members and key management personnel to disclose any interests that could be considered related parties. This includes familial relationships, business interests, or any other connections that might result in related party transactions;\n - A system for regular (e.g., annual) declarations of interests from board members and key personnel to update any changes in their relationships or interests;\n - The definition of a robust approval processes requiring related party transactions to be approved by the board or a designated board committee. This process should exclude any board members with a conflict of interest from the decision-making process;\n - The requirement to maintain a register for recording related party transactions;\n - Where your ministry transacts with related parties, those transactions must be covered by a written agreement (contract);  and\n - All transactions made with the related party must be recorded in the register (the ACNC provides a template to use for this).\n\nThe ACNC provides a very helpful guide to related party transactions, tailored to organisation size, and defines what needs to be reported in your Annual Information Statement.',
