      'If you are a public company, it is essential to maintain accurate and up-to-date records with ASIC to ensure compliance with the Corporations Act 2001.  Failure to notify ASIC of significant changes within the required timeframe may result in penalties or legal consequences for the company and its directors.\n\nIncorporated Association rules vary by jurisdiction, but failure to update your local authority of substantive changes could lead to administrative penalties or fines, the loss of certain legal protections or benefits, access to government funding, loss of tax-exempt status, difficulty in legal proceedings, reputational damage or - in extreme cases of persistent non-compliance, the jurisdictional authorities may take steps to dissolve the incorporated association, resulting in the termination of its legal existence.\n\nThe Board should review any and all changes made since registration or the last jurisdictional update (whichever was the most recent) and move to report these changes to the relevant authorities as soon as possible.',
