      "A good rate of attendance at board meetings would typically be around 75% or higher. This means that most board members are consistently present at meetings, actively participating in discussions, and contributing to decision-making processes.\n\nHowever, it's important to recognise that occasional absences are inevitable due to conflicts with other commitments, illness, or personal reasons. Therefore, some degree of flexibility is reasonable.\n\nConsistently low attendance rates can be a cause for concern as it may indicate disengagement or lack of commitment from board members. It can also impede the board's ability to function effectively and fulfill its responsibilities.\n\nTo promote higher attendance rates, the Board should:\n\n - Establish clear expectations for attendance in board member position descriptions and in the Governance Policy.\n - Schedule meetings well in advance to accommodate board members' schedules.\n - Provide opportunities for remote participation through video conferencing or teleconferencing.\n - Encourage open communication and transparency regarding scheduling conflicts.\n - Assess the reasons behind low attendance and address any underlying issues proactively.\n\nIf the poor attendance is predominantly due to particular Board members who persistently fail to attend without notice or good reason, and if that behaviour does not alter after appropriate feedback, the Board should consider removing these members and appointing others who are more able to fulfil their obligations and make good contribution.",
