    risk_id: '10',
    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "Minutes of a board meeting should ideally be published as soon as possible after the meeting while still ensuring accuracy and completeness. A common practice is to distribute draft minutes to board members within a week following the meeting. This allows board members to review the minutes while the discussions are still fresh in their minds and provide any necessary corrections or clarifications.\n\nOnce any feedback or revisions have been incorporated, the finalized minutes should be distributed to board members promptly, typically within a few days to a week after the meeting. This ensures that board members have access to an accurate record of the proceedings in a timely manner, facilitating accountability, transparency, and informed decision-making.\n\nIn some jurisdictions, the guidelines around minute taking and publishing must be included in your organisation's constitution.  Where this is not mandated, it is still best practice to do so.  The Board should review, and if necessarily update, the constitution to define the timelines for the preparation and distribution of minutes.  Alternately these may be defined in in the Model Practice: Conducting Effective Board Meetings.",
