      'Gaining a clear, shared understanding of key internal and external stakeholders will help an NFP board to effectively guide the organisation and fulfill its mission. \n\nThe Board should conduct a workshop with board members and senior leadership to identify and categorise all stakeholders, both internal and external, creating a stakeholder map that visually represents the relationships and influences of various stakeholders.  This can help in understanding the dynamics and prioritising stakeholders based on their impact and interest.\n\nClearly define and categorise stakeholders into internal (e.g., employees, volunteers, board members) and external groups (e.g., donors, beneficiaries, partners, regulatory bodies).  Consider what regular communication channels (such as newsletters, emails, or forums) could keep stakeholders informed and engaged.  Importantly, the Board should ensure that its own composition includes balanced representation from key stakeholder groups.  This will promote the alignment of organisational strategies to stakeholder imperatives.\n\nFor organisations of larger scale, the Board may consider establishing advisory committees from various stakeholder groups that can provide regular input and advice on specific issues or projects.  There may also be benefit in providing training sessions for board members on stakeholder management and engagement strategies, including workshops on communication skills, conflict resolution, and cultural competency.',
