      'Incorporating stakeholder feedback into the strategic Board decision-making processes is important for ensuring that the organisation remains responsive, effective, and aligned with the needs and expectations of its stakeholders. \n\nKey methods of including stakeholder feedback into decision making processes include having stakeholders represented on the Board, establishing advisory committees that include representatives from key stakeholder groups, deploying regular surveys to collect feedback from different stakeholder groups, focus groups and workshops to engage stakeholders in more in-depth discussions about specific issues, programs, or strategic directions.\n\nFor larger organisations, consider conducting public consultations for major decisions or strategic changes. This can include town hall meetings, public forums, or online consultations where stakeholders can voice their opinions and ask questions.\n\nThe Board should review these feedback options and identify whether any of these, or other means of securing feedback, can be used to improve the inputs to Board decision making.',
