    action_text:
      'Your assessment reports mixed views about how safe Board members feel to express their views. \n\nWhen a Board fails to create a trusting and safe space where people feel free to share their views without fear of recrimination, it exposes the organisation to several significant risks.  Poor decision-making, groupthink, decreased engagement and morale, the erosion of trust, compromised transparency, conflict, and higher turnover can arise.  \n\nA culture where people fear recrimination can become toxic, characterised by fear, anxiety, and a lack of collaboration and support.  Reputational damage and stakeholder dissatisfaction, even legal and ethical risks - and in severe cases, whistleblower actions - can result.\n\nThe Board must address this issue as a priority.  The following actions are recommended:\n\n1. Clearly articulate the organisation’s commitment to openness, respect, and inclusivity in all communications and actions.  Ensure that these values are documented and embedded in the organisational culture.\n\n2. Develop\/review\/update an organisational code of conduct that outlines expected behaviors, emphasising respect, inclusivity, and the importance of diverse perspectives.  Ensure all board members, staff, and volunteers are aware of and adhere to this code.  See our Model Policy: Code of Conduct as a starting point.\n\n3. Be clear about Board decision making processes.  Consider adopting a formal practice, such as our Model Practice: Board Decision Making, which guides Boards in the process of conducting Board meetings and making decisions.\n\n4. Provide training for board members and leaders on active listening techniques to ensure they can genuinely listen and respond to feedback without judgment or interruption.\n\n5. Use facilitation techniques that ensure all voices are heard, such as round-robin or structured turn-taking.\n\n6. Board members and senior leaders should model the behavior they expect from others. Demonstrate openness, humility, and a willingness to learn from others.',
