      "Poor collaboration in NFP Boards can deeply affect the Board's governance effectiveness, which in turn has a negative influence over the outcomes and impacts of the wider organisation.\n\nPoor collaboration can arise from:\n - Lack of clear roles and responsibilities,\n - Conflicting priorities and agendas\n - Ineffective or inadequate communication\n - Insufficient alignment on mission and goals:\n - Dominance by a subset of Board members\n - Inadequate conflict resolution mechanisms\n - Cultural and personality differences\n - Ineffective leadership\n\nThe Board should consider these causal factors for poor collaboration and consider how it might structurally address these.  Options the Board should consider include:\n\n - Clarify roles and responsibilities - see our Template: Board Roles and Responsibilities as a starting point.\n - Align on mission and goals - review and reinforce the organisation’s mission, vision, and strategic goals to ensure all board members are working towards common objectives.  Invite any Board members who are not aligned to reconsider their participation in the organisation.\n - Establish clear and inclusive decision-making processes that ensure all voices are heard and considered. Encourage collaborative decision-making rather than allowing a few members to dominate.\n - Ensure there is a Template: Board Dispute Resolution Policy and Procedure, and consider offering training in conflict resolution and mediation to equip board members with the skills to address and resolve disputes constructively.\n - Ensure effective leadership by appointing a strong chair who can guide the board, facilitate collaboration, and encourage active participation.\n - Conduct regular GovernApp assessments to assess board performance and dynamics. Use the generated action plans to identify areas for improvement and implement the recommended changes to enhance collaboration.",
