    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      'Dysfunctional written and verbal communications within the Board can have several negative impacts on the organisation, including misunderstandings and confusion, delayed decisions, increased errors, frustration and disengagement, and even strategic misalignment.  This can escalate to conflict and prolonged disputes.\n\nTo improve written and verbal communications within the Board, the following mechanisms should be considered:\n\n - Have structured agendas for Board and committee meetings to keep meetings focused and efficient.\n - Ensure accurate and detailed minutes are taken during meetings, capturing key decisions, action items, and responsibilities. Distribute these minutes promptly after meetings.\n - Use a standardised template for minutes to ensure consistency and clarity.\n - Implement a round-robin format in meetings where each board member provides updates on their area of responsibility. This ensures all voices are heard and fosters comprehensive communication.\n - Encourage members to ask clarifying questions during meetings to ensure understanding and to address any ambiguities immediately.\n - Use clear and specific subject lines on emails to make it easy to understand the email’s purpose at a glance. This helps prioritise and manage emails effectively.\n - Keep email communications concise and well-structured. Use bullet points, numbered lists, and headings to enhance readability and ensure key points are easily identified.\n - Utilise designated platforms or tools (like Board management software) that centralise communications, document sharing, and collaboration. \n - Leverage video conferencing tools for virtual meetings to enhance verbal communication. Use features like screen sharing and virtual whiteboards to facilitate more interactive and engaging discussions.\n\nBy implementing some of these mechanisms, Boards can enhance the clarity, efficiency, and effectiveness of their written and verbal communications, leading to better decision-making and governance.',
