      'Healthy Boards will operate with openness and transparency, and feedback - real time or after the fact - will occur as a matter of course.  In less well developed Boards, and in scenarios where non-Board members may wish to provide feedback, clarity about how to provide feedback is helpful.\n\nThe Board may consider adopting the following basic feedback process:\n\n - Establish an online feedback form that is accessible to all stakeholders, including staff, volunteers, and members. Ensure it is user-friendly and can be submitted anonymously if desired.\n - Set up a dedicated email address for feedback, managed by a designated person or committee to ensure confidentiality and prompt responses.\n - Clearly communicate the feedback process to all stakeholders through multiple channels, such as emails, newsletters, and meetings.\n - Provide guidelines on how to give constructive feedback, including examples of useful feedback and the types of issues that can be raised.\n - Organise feedback sessions or town hall meetings where stakeholders can provide verbal feedback directly to board members.\n - Acknowledge the receipt of feedback promptly.\n - Develop and implement action plans to address the feedback. Assign responsibilities and set deadlines for resolving issues or making improvements.\n - Communicate the actions taken in response to feedback to the stakeholders, demonstrating that their input is valued and leads to tangible changes.',
