    text: "I'm not sure.",
    detailed: null,
    score: '0.00',
    is_triggering_action: '1',
    risk_id: '30',
    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "Ideally, an NFP Board should first see a draft budget at least three months in advance of the new financial year. This allows ample time for Board members have enough time to thoroughly review the draft budget, understand the assumptions and projections, and ensure alignment with the strategic plan.  \n\nSufficient time for board members to provide constructive feedback and request necessary revisions needs to be allowed for.  If changes are requested then the finance committee and management team can refine the budget based on the board's input, ensuring it is realistic and achievable.\n\nOverall, the timeline for budget approval needs to allow for review and changes so the board can formally approve the final budget well before the start of the new financial year, ensuring there is no gap in financial planning.  Further, operational teams need reasonable time to align their operational plans and activities with the approved budget, ensuring a smooth transition into the new financial year.\n\nThe Board should set clear expectations with the Executive Leadership around when the first draft budget should be presented.  As the budget should reflect the broader Strategic Plan, the Board needs to have shared at least a solid draft of any new or updated Strategic Plan with those preparing the budget so that the draft budget aligns with the Strategic Plan.",
    created_at: '2025-02-24 04:36:25',
