    action_text:
      "Your assessment results indicate that the Board does not have a good and shared understanding of a profit and loss statement.\n\nA profit and loss statement (otherwise known as an income statement) lists revenues coming into an organisation and expenses incurred by the organisation. It tells you how much profit you're making, or how much you're losing. Profit and loss statements are typically reviewed every month, quarter and year.  \n\nFor NFPs, income includes donations, grants, membership fees.  Expenses relate to the cost of running the organisation and monies expended in the pursuit of the NFP's goals, such a program delivery.   Note, expenses do not include the purchase of capital goods or assets, but can include depreciation of assets.\n\nNet profit is the money left over after you paid expenses. Net profit is calculated by subtracting expenses from sales.  Note, NFPs can make profit (often referred to in NFPs as \"surplus\".  In fact, to be sustainable, NFPs must take in more revenue than they spend in the longer term, or they will become financially unviable and consequerntly unable to deliver on their organisational outcomes.  The difference for NFPs is that they are not permitted to distribute profit to members or shareholders.\n\nUnderstanding the profit and loss statement is a core skill for Board members.  The Board should review our guide to what comprises revenue and expenses for a not-for-profit in our model practice.  The Board may also wish to consider acquiring additional training in reading and understanding financial statement for Boards.",
    created_at: '2025-02-24 21:37:46',
