    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "An engaged and satisfied workforce is a major contributor to organisational success.  As such, regularly measuring employee and volunteer engagement and satisfaction is a helpful tool for Boards and executives to understand where engagement is at, identify areas for improvement, and implement strategies to enhance overall satisfaction and commitment. \n\nThe most common means of measuring staff and volunteer engagement is an engagement survey.  Typically run annually or every second year, engagement surveys address questions about job satisfaction, alignment with the organisation's mission, understanding of roles, opportunities for growth, and overall morale.\n\nIn times of rapid change, pulse surveys - shorter, more frequent surveys - can be used to gauge the immediate mood and engagement levels. These can help in identifying issues in real-time.\n\nOther passive measures of engagement include:\n - the results of employee and volunteer exit surveys, which help understand their reasons for leaving and gather feedback on their experience;\n - retention rates of employees and volunteers - high turnover can indicate low engagement;\n - the frequency and consistency of volunteer participation as a measure of volunteers commitment.\n\nThe Board should consider scheduling a regular (annual or every two years) structured survey that can yield actionable data to help improve staff and volunteer engagement and satisfaction.",
