    is_triggering_action: '1',
    risk_id: '20',
    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "The Board should urgently review the organisation's governing document to understand whether it accurately and fairly reflects its current purposes.  If not, the document should be updated appropriately.  It is good practice to review your governing document periodically to ensure the alignment of stated purpose and current practice.  Your constitution (or equivalent) should ideally state this review period.\n\nHelpful steps to updating governing documents are:\n\n1. Conduct a thorough review of the charity’s current activities and purposes. Ensure that the updated purposes align with the charity's mission and activities.\n2. Seek guidance from legal experts or relevant regulatory bodies such as the ACNC to ensure that proposed changes comply with legal requirements.\n3. Draft the necessary amendments to the governing document. This may include changes to the objects clause, activities, or operational areas.\n4. Present the proposed amendments to the charity’s board for approval. Ensure that board members fully understand the changes and their implications.\n5. If the charity has members, the proposed amendments may need to be approved at a general meeting of members. Follow the procedures outlined in the governing document for making amendments.\n6. Notify the ACNC of the changes to the charity’s purposes. Depending on the charity’s legal structure, you may also need to inform other regulatory bodies, such as ASIC or state-based regulators.\n\nNote, the ACNC has 12 defined charitable purposes.  Organisations cannot be registered as charities if their purpose does not fall under one or more of these categories.  \n\n1. Advancing health\n2. Advancing education\n3. Advancing social or public welfare\n4. Advancing religion\n5. Advancing culture\n6. Promoting reconciliation, mutual respect and tolerance between groups of individuals that are in Australia\n7. Promoting or protecting human rights\n8. Advancing the security or safety of Australia or the Australian public\n9. Preventing or relieving the suffering of animals\n10. Advancing the natural environment\n11. Any other purpose beneficial to the public, analogous to, or within the spirit of, any of the purposes above\n12. Promoting or opposing change to a matter of law, policy or practice in relation to any of the purposes above",
    created_at: '2025-03-13 02:28:26',
