    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "Your responses suggest that the Board is unsure if its funds and assets are used solely for its charitable purposes.  \n\nTo qualify as a Charity your organisation must by definition in its rules, constitution or trust deed be defined as, and operate as, a not-for profit.  While this does not preclude charities from making profits (a surplus of revenue over expenses), any profits must be used to further the purposes of the organisation and its beneficiaries.  Profits may not be distributed to Members or other related stakeholders.\n\nYour Board should address its current uncertainty by reflecting on the following items and address any gaps to ensure that your charity uses its funds and assets solely for its charitable purposes:\n\n - Establish a clear mission statement that defines the charity's purpose and objectives.\n - Ensure that all activities align with this mission.\n - Implement a strong governance framework with clear roles and responsibilities for board members and management. This includes regular board meetings, documented decision-making processes, and conflict of interest policies (assessing your Board using the GovernApp Four Frames Assessment Framework will provide great help in this area)\n - Establish stringent financial controls, including regular audits and financial reporting. This ensures that funds are used appropriately and discrepancies are identified and addressed promptly.\n - Develop and enforce a conflict of interest policy. Board members and staff must disclose any personal interests that could influence their decisions.\n - Honour the intent of donors by ensuring that restricted funds are used for their specified purposes. Keep detailed records of how these funds are spent.\n - Provide regular reports to stakeholders, including detailed accounts of how funds are used. This can be achieved through annual reports, financial statements, and updates on the charity's website.\n - Engage external auditors or advisors to review financial and operational activities. Independent oversight helps ensure that the charity operates within legal and ethical boundaries.\n - Implement a whistleblower policy that allows staff and volunteers to report any misuse of funds or assets confidentially. Protect whistleblowers from retaliation.\n\nBy implementing these mechanisms and adhering to best practices, a charity can effectively safeguard its funds and assets, ensuring they are used solely for its intended charitable purposes.",
    created_at: '2025-03-13 04:30:44',
