    risk_id: '20',
    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "Your responses suggest that the Board is unsure how the organisation's activities help it pursue its charitable purposes.  \n\nA charitable purpose is essentially the mission of the organisation.  A charity undertakes activities in support of its overarching purpose.  It is important for your charity to be able to explain how your activities contribute toward achieving your charitable purpose(s).  \n\nTo gain clarity about the link between activity and purpose, the following strategies can help.  Reflect on these strategies and determine which to implement that will help you most effectively demonstrate the linking of your activities to your mission.\n\n - Explicitly connect each activity to the charity’s stated purposes. For example, if a charity’s purpose is to provide education to underprivileged children, describe how specific educational programs or scholarships fulfill this purpose.\n - Develop and use metrics to measure the outcomes of activities. For instance, if a charity provides healthcare services, metrics might include the number of patients treated, improvements in health outcomes, or community health statistics.\n - Include a detailed section in the annual report that maps activities to charitable purposes. Explain how each major activity contributes to achieving the mission.\n - Provide clear financial reports that show how funds are allocated towards activities that fulfill the charitable purposes.\n - Conduct regular evaluations of programs and projects to assess their effectiveness in achieving the charity’s goals.\n - Use independent evaluations or audits to provide an unbiased assessment of how well activities are aligned with purposes.\n - Use the charity’s website, newsletters, and social media platforms to regularly communicate how activities support the mission. Highlight specific projects and their outcomes.\n - Ensure compliance with reporting requirements set by regulatory bodies like the Australian Charities and Not-for-profits Commission (ACNC). This often includes demonstrating how activities support the charitable purposes.",
    created_at: '2025-03-13 04:39:30',
    updated_at: '2025-03-13 04:39:30',
