      "While Responsible People are volunteers kindly giving their time, Charities should still undertake reviews of the skills and performance of these volunteers.  Poor performance among Responsible People can impede the effective operation of your Board as whole, and can have a negative flow-on effect on the wider organisation.\n\nThe starting point for all performance reviews are the expectations of a person in a role.  To this end, all Responsible Persons should have a clear Position Description defining the skills, attributes and objectives for their role.\n\nResponsible Persons should undergo review on a regular basis, such as annually.  The review should consider the Person's Position Description plus related artefacts such as the Code of Conduct and COnflict of Interest policies.  Any performance issues arising from reviews can be addressed by training, mentoring, or on-the-job skills transfer.  Charities may wish to consider implementing professional development plans for Responsible Persons who are not meeting expectations.  \n\nNote, capable Responsible Persons performing well may find a directive to have a Professional Development Plan to be an onerous barrier to participation.\n\nOrganisations lacking a Board review and development practice should consider adopting a practice based on the GovernApp Model Practice: Board Skills and Traits Identification provided.",
