    is_na: '0',
    action_text:
      "If your charity likely to be, identified as being involved in the abuse of a person by being subject to a redress application, or been identified in a response to a request for information under the Redress Act, you should immediately (if you are not already):\n\n - Adopt a posture of full cooperation with the Redress Scheme, which includes providing any requested information and complying with its processes.\n - Inform the Board and Legal Counsel. Legal advice, including external, independent advice, is crucial to ensure compliance with all obligations under the Redress Act and other relevant laws.\n - Conduct an internal review to understand the circumstances that led to the involvement in the abuse. This review should be thorough and may involve external experts to ensure impartiality.\n - Provide appropriate support to the survivors of the abuse. This may include counseling, financial compensation, or other forms of redress as determined by the National Redress Scheme.\n\nThere are also ongoing and preventive actions your Charity should consider in addition.\n\n - Review and strengthen child protection policies, safeguarding procedures, and any other relevant governance structures to prevent future instances of abuse.\n - Ensure these policies are communicated effectively throughout the organization.\n - Provide training for all staff and volunteers on safeguarding practices and their responsibilities under the Redress Act.\n - Promote a culture of zero tolerance for abuse and emphasize the importance of protecting vulnerable individuals.\n - Be transparent with stakeholders, including donors, members, and the broader community, about the charity's involvement and the steps being taken to address it.\n - Regularly report on the progress of implementing safeguarding measures and compliance with the Redress Scheme.\n - Implement ongoing monitoring to ensure compliance with safeguarding policies and the Redress Scheme.",
